it, you canâ€™t do it. In the United States, itâ€™s not a crime. The consequence is that, in the United States, holocaust denial is unknown. Thereâ€™s plenty of it. You know, thereâ€™s professors at universities who publish books denying the holocaust. Nobody pays any attention to them. [â€¦] In France, and a lot of Europe, itâ€™s all over the front pages. A ton of publicity. [â€¦] some guy somewhere does some marginal thing, and everybody knows about it. Itâ€™s a way of giving publicity to holocaust denial. [â€¦] I just donâ€™t think itâ€™s even tactically the right way to deal with, say, neo-fascist groups. And it does give them an argument [â€¦]. They can claim freedom of speech, which is a value we all uphold. So we should uphold it and then win the argumentâ€. Journalist Glenn Greenwald seems to concur. In a 2017 Al Jazeera debate, he said, â€œThereâ€™s no such thing as banning ideas. It has never worked.â€ He believed that in a perfect world one could perhaps outlaw bigoted ideas. â€œThe opposite is true, though,â€ he said. â€œWhen you try and do it, you turn them into martyrs. You actually make them stronger.â€ This is not to say the handful of people who displayed the flag among tens of thousands of Black Monday protesters were â€œneo-fascistâ€ white supremacists. The truth is we may never know, because none were asked. Not a single â€œflag-waverâ€ was taken to court. The more likely explanation is that they were protesting crime, just like those of other races who have used the old flag in this manner (see Part II). VI The proponents of broad hate speech laws argue that too much freedom of expression is dangerous. By limiting it, people would be free to conduct their lives unmolested â€“ without having to endure obscene, offensive or hurtful views. This then leads to peacable and civilised societies, and hateful groups can be restrained. The problem is that censorship tends to backfire. Not only does it make people suspicious of one another, but it also sometimes turns them into opportunists, while the state only consolidates its power. Consider the example of Rwanda. After its own painful past, the country passed numerous laws to try and deter hate speech and â€œfoster unityâ€. These laws, many of which were criminal in nature, dealt with â€œgenocide ideologyâ€ and â€œsectarianismâ€ (or â€œdivisionismâ€). Amnesty International published two reports â€“ Safer to stay silent (2010) and Unsafe to speak out (2011) â€“ that describe how these laws stifled freedom of expression[8][9]. â€œThe vague wording of the laws is deliberately exploited to violate human rights,â€ one report reads. These were then used to â€œcriminalise criticism of government and legitimate dissent.â€ Human rights activists, journalists and opposition politicians started getting prosecuted under these laws and â€œdenunciation became part of everyday lifeâ€. Citizens, even neighbours, used them to settle personal scores â€“ â€œincluding to discredit teachers, for local political capital, to acquire land and in the context of personal disputes.â€ Many prosecutions were politically motivated and proceedings often dealt mainly with the accusedâ€™s â€œalleged underlying philosophyâ€, instead of by proper legal analysis. As such the laws were having a â€œcorrosive effect on mutual trustâ€ and the organisation said it hoped amendments would be passed to only prohibit expression when it contained an element of incitement. In the South African literature, some academics argue the Equality Act only aims to prohibit â€œlow-valueâ€ expression, and moreover provides for â€œlenientâ€ restorative measures. However, several fines of R150Â 000 have already been handed down. Claims can furthermore be referred for prosecution, and the Hate Crimes and Hate Speech Bill is still looming[10]. Conclusion Many intellectuals like to harangue the public about class, privilege and power, but often appear not to believe â€˜the peopleâ€™ are good or capable enough to manage their own fundamental rights â€“ as this case illustrates. Their ardent support for only allowing certain displays of the flag â€“ in other words, by themselves â€“ is not unlike the kind of free speech enjoyed by some in China. In China, freedom of expression is a â€œprivilege, not a rightâ€. The authorities have reportedly softened towards accepting criticism, but only from â€œcertain categories of peopleâ€ â€“ the â€œfree speech eliteâ€. A report from the United States Congressional Commission on China explains how Chinese society is profoundly hierarchical, despite the countryâ€™s compassionate socialist constitution. The Chinese intellectual and professional elite comprises mainly senior government officials, with academics and journalists slotting in beneath and yet among their ranks. Academics and editors can therefore criticise the government to some extent, depending on their â€œideological credentialsâ€. The authorities will not however accept the same from private individuals, and there is â€œno freedom of political expression for ordinary citizensâ€. Exercising this freedom carries the risk of prosecution for subversion. Controversial issues inevitably provoke a range of responses in any democratic society, and it is important for these to be expressed. What is disconcerting however is the clearly enthusiastic enjoyment of this freedom in the abandonment of its defence. It is especially concerning when one considers that for many opponents this right is the lifeblood of their professional existence. And despite the many strident opinions, the ensuing debate made it clear that few had any notion of the case, nor its implications, nor even of AfriForumâ€™s role in it. The lack of freedom of expression under apartheid led to many profoundly unjust absurdities. It would be a shame to repeat the mistake. Follow MLA on TwitterÂ @MLAntoni [1] Fiona McCleod (Compiled by) & Felicity Kaganas (Compiled by)Â (1985)Â Statement on Sentencing,Â South African Journal on Huma